Qlik Sense Advanced Patterns and Best Practices — Architecture Admin > Section Access and Security > Basic Structure

```qlik
Section Access;
LOAD * INLINE [
ACCESS, USERID, PASSWORD, [FIELD_NAME]
ADMIN, ADMIN_USER, admin123,
USER, john.doe@company.co.za, pass123, ZA
USER, jane.smith@company.co.za, pass456, UK
USER, *,, *
];

Section Application;
// Normal data load below
```

Qlik Sense Advanced Patterns and Best Practices — Architecture Admin > Section Access and Security > Data Reduction (Row-Level Security)

The field name in Section Access must match a field name in the app data. Qlik automatically filters rows so each user only sees their own data.

```qlik
Section Access;
LOAD * INLINE [
ACCESS, USERID, REGION
ADMIN, admin@company.co.za,
USER, john.doe@company.co.za, ZA
USER, jane.smith@company.co.za, UK
];

Section Application;
Transactions:
LOAD *, Region FROM transactions.qvd (qvd);
// User john.doe will only see rows where Region='ZA'
```

Qlik Sense Advanced Patterns and Best Practices — Architecture Admin > Section Access and Security > Dynamic Data Reduction

Use a separate table for access control (loaded from a secure source):

```qlik
Section Access;
UserAccess:
SQL SELECT ACCESS, USERID, REGION FROM security_db.dbo.UserAccessRights;

Section Application;
```

Qlik Sense Advanced Patterns and Best Practices — Architecture Admin > Section Access and Security > OMIT Fields

Fields listed in `OMIT` column are hidden from that user:

```qlik
Section Access;
LOAD * INLINE [
ACCESS, USERID, OMIT
USER, standard_user, Salary; CostPrice
ADMIN, admin_user,
];
```

